\begin_body

\begin_layout Part*
Monte Carlo Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation governing this is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c}\frac{d}{dt}I\left(r,\hat{s}\right)+\frac{d}{d\hat{s}}I\left(r,\hat{s}\right)+\mu_{t}I\left(r,\hat{s}\right)-\mu_{s}\intop_{4\pi}I\left(r,\hat{s'}\right)p\left(\hat{s'},\hat{s}\right)d\Omega'=\epsilon\left(r,\hat{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Creating the photon package and propagating it, with probabilistic interaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the energy of a package 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 reaches a certain threshold we perform:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\leftarrow\begin{cases}
mW & w.p.\frac{1}{m}\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
Diffusion Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
RTE to Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the decomposition to spherical harmonics, we notice that the first
 2 terms describe the energy density and the flux density.
 If we assume diffusion, these are the only 2 orders we care about.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This measn that we can approxiame:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\left(r,\hat{s}\right)\approx\frac{U\left(r\right)}{4\pi}+\frac{3}{4\pi}J\left(r\right)\cdot\hat{s}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is not dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we will find the 2 equations governing by first integrating
 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{4\pi}d\Omega$
\end_inset

 and second integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{4\pi}\hat{s}d\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c}\frac{d}{dt}U+\mu_{a}U+\nabla\cdot J=S_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c}\frac{d}{dt}J+\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)J+\frac{1}{3}\nabla U=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{c\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}\left|\frac{d}{dt}J\right|\ll\left|J\right|$
\end_inset

 then we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=-D\nabla U
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\frac{1}{3\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c}\frac{d}{dt}U+\mu_{a}U-\nabla\cdot\left(D\nabla U\right)=S_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is constant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{c}\frac{d}{dt}U+\mu_{a}U-D\nabla^{2}U=S_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Green function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For time domain we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\propto\frac{e^{-\mu_{a}c_{0}\left(t-t'\right)}}{\left(t-t'\right)^{3/2}}e^{-\frac{\left|r-r'\right|^{2}}{4Dc_{0}\left(t-t'\right)}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For frequency domain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\frac{e^{i\sqrt{-\frac{\mu_{a}}{D}+i\frac{\omega}{Dc_{0}}}\left|r-r'\right|}}{4\pi\left|r-r'\right|}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can notice that for low frequencies we get the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{eff}=\sqrt{\frac{\mu_{a}}{D}}=\sqrt{3\mu_{a}\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Boundary condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For index matched media (Robin boundary condition):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U-2J\cdot\hat{n}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Point source approximation for external illumination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that at 
\begin_inset Formula $l'=\frac{1}{\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'}=\frac{1}{\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}\left(1-g\right)}$
\end_inset

 the light is diffusive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a pencil beam at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is like a diffusive source at 
\begin_inset Formula $l'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Robin boundary condition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $J=-D\nabla U$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U-2D\frac{d}{dz}U=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using taylor expansion and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=z_{b}=-2D$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(-2D\right)-2D\frac{d}{dz}U\left(-2D\right)=0\Rightarrow U\left(-2D\right)\approx0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a new boundary condition we will use.
 Using the method of images.
 Thus have the pencil source as a diffusive source at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=l'$
\end_inset

, and we add an opposite source at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=-l'-4D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the solution is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\frac{1}{4\pi D}\left[\frac{e^{-\mu_{eff}r_{1}}}{r_{1}}-\frac{e^{-\mu_{eff}r_{2}}}{r_{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{1}{4\pi D}\left[\frac{e^{-\mu_{eff}\sqrt{\left(z-z_{0}\right)^{2}+\rho^{2}}}}{\sqrt{\left(z-z_{0}\right)^{2}+\rho^{2}}}-\frac{e^{-\mu_{eff}\sqrt{\left(z+z_{0}+2z_{b}\right)^{2}+\rho^{2}}}}{\sqrt{\left(z+z_{0}+2z_{b}\right)^{2}+\rho^{2}}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside: When does 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}=-z_{0}-2z_{b}$
\end_inset

 This forces 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}=-z_{b}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{0}=l'=\frac{1}{\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{b}=2D=\frac{2}{3\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}\Rightarrow-z_{0}-2z_{b}=-\frac{1}{\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}\left[1+\frac{4}{3}\right]=-\frac{7}{3\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow l'=-D
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\frac{1}{\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}=-\frac{1}{3\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\frac{1}{\left(\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'\right)}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow\mu_{a}+\mu_{s}'=\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that we reach results for relatively high 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a},\mu_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 (which causes the problem with the k-wave reconstruction).
 A better regression is needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
1D Tests
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Test A
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{x}=N_{y}=150$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dx=dy=0.1mm$
\end_inset

.
 Using full side illumination with isotropic illumination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a}=0.001\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{s}=0.1\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a,rect}=0.01\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=0.9
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We got:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{eff,expected}=0.0057\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{eff,regression}=0.097\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This does not follow what we expect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Test B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using values for skin taken from:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10765-019-2515-3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a}=0.1\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{s}=10\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a,rect}=0.3\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=0.9
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We got:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{eff,expected}=0.574\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{eff,regression}=0.528\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Test C
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a}=0.5\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{s}=10\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{a,rect}=1.5\frac{1}{mm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=0.9
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We got:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
